web/params.json:82:      "source": "Populations in the causal mortality studies are low-income adults roughly age 50-64. Remaining life expectancy ~26y is calibrated to [Chetty et al. (2016, JAMA)](https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2513561): bottom-income-quartile life expectancy at 40 is ~78 (men) to ~83 (women), implying mid-20s remaining years around age 55. Utility ~0.78 is calibrated to US EQ-5D population norms (e.g., [Jiang et al. 2021](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11136-020-02650-y), ages 55-64 ~0.80 overall, lower at low income). Discounted at 3% with a half-cycle correction."
web/params.json:111:      "source": "Derived from [GiveWell's current impact estimates](https://www.givewell.org/impact-estimates) of cost per life saved, 2022-2024 program averages: ~$4,000 (Malaria Consortium seasonal chemoprevention) to ~$5,500 (AMF nets), figures GiveWell rounds up to the nearest $500. Treating those as ~2023 dollars and inflating by [CPI-U](https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS) 335.123/304.702 = 1.10 gives ~$4,400-$6,050 per life. A child death averted at ~age 1 with ~65 remaining life-years, discounted at 3% with half-cycle correction (annuity ~28.9) and utility ~0.87, is ~25.1 discounted QALYs, giving endpoints of ~$175-$241 per QALY-equivalent; the loguniform {150, 260} widens that for conversion uncertainty (utility, remaining years, price level). An earlier revision also used a 2015 AMF figure ($3,340/life, itself already a discounted-QALY-era calculation, in ~2015 dollars); it is retired here in favor of GiveWell's current program averages."
web/params.json:173:      "identification": "DD across staggered state Medicaid expansions with linked coverage data (Sommers 2017; Miller, Johnson & Wherry 2021 corroborate with linked administrative mortality for the ACA expansion). Strong; the Oregon HIE RCT (null on 2-yr physical health measures) tempers it, hence not the top tier.",
web/params.json:196:      "source": "[Bailey & Goodman-Bacon (2015), AER 105(3)](https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.20120070) ([full text](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4436657/)) report \"a cost-per-year-of-life ratio of approximately $54,000\" for CHCs in 2012 dollars (Medicare comparison: $161,373-$459,000 per life-year, i.e. CHCs at 1/8 to 1/3 the cost). Inflated with [FRED CPI-U](https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS) from the 2012 annual average 229.594 to May 2026 335.123 (x1.460): ~$79k per life-year; the loguniform $55k-$115k places ~\u00b145% around that point estimate. The model divides by the utility-weight draw to convert life-years to QALYs (the prior revision skipped that conversion and used an invented Medicare prior; both fixed here)."
web/params.json:211:      "source": "Anchors are 2000s-era nominal ICERs and are inflated here. The [Community Guide review](https://www.thecommunityguide.org/findings/mental-health-and-mental-illness-collaborative-care-management-depressive-disorders.html) reports the Gilbody-era $17k-$39k/QALY range in 2008 dollars, which [CPI-U](https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS) 335.123/215.303 = 1.56 inflates to ~$26k-$61k; the systematic review at [van Steenbergen-Weijenburg et al. (2010), BMC Health Services Research 10:19](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/1472-6963-10-19) reports study ICERs of ~$21.5k-$49.5k without year normalization (similar-era dollars, similar inflated magnitude; an earlier revision misattributed this link to \"Gilbody et al. 2006\" and pooled the two reviews' endpoints as one range). Together the inflated cost-effective case sits around $26k-$77k. The upper tail extends toward [Grochtdreis et al. (2015)](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0123078), whose healthcare-perspective ICERs reach $153,299 in 2012 international dollars (not CPI-converted here; international dollars are not US CPI dollars). The 5th/95th prior {25k, 150k} brackets the inflated evidence."
web/params.json:218:      "identification": "Dollars route here by delivery geography: the non-US share of each organization's reported service locations, applied to its health-relevant focus areas (src/msqaly/allocation.py). The routed portfolio spans GiveWell-grade programs backed by RCTs (Malaria Consortium $10M, Evidence Action $20M, GiveDirectly's global program $50M+$5M) through strong community-health-worker and health-systems organizations (Living Goods $25M+$3.5M, Muso $15M, Amref $50M, Partners In Health $50M, Noora Health $20M, icddr,b $16M) to partial-health-tagged organizations. strong_quasi reflects that mix.",
web/params.json:226:      "source": "Pricing a non-US health dollar at US anchors understates it by orders of magnitude \u2014 the correction a reader prompted. The 90% CI $300-$4,000 per QALY (2026$) spans [GiveWell's current program averages](https://www.givewell.org/impact-estimates) (~$4,000-5,500 per under-5 life saved ~ $175-241 per discounted QALY, the marquee floor sitting just below this range's low end), community-health-worker and systems programs GiveWell scores in the low single-digit multiples of cash (~$500-2,000 per QALY-equivalent), and [GiveDirectly's global cash program](https://blog.givewell.org/2024/11/12/re-evaluating-the-impact-of-unconditional-cash-transfers/) (child-mortality channel ~ $8,000 per discounted QALY, above this range's high end \u2014 the tail covers it). Gift amounts verified in [Yield Giving's database](https://yieldgiving.com/gifts)."
web/params.json:271:      "source": "Point anchor: [Holtgrave et al. (2013), AIDS and Behavior 17(5)](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10461-012-0204-3) report $62,493/QALY for the Housing & Health intervention \u2014 an HIV-positive, unstably-housed cohort (2004-2008 study), NOT general chronic homelessness. The team's [underlying cost analysis](https://shnny.org/uploads/Cost_and_Threshold_Analysis_of_Housing_as_an_HIV_Prevention.pdf) is stated in 2005 dollars; inflating by [CPI-U](https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS) 335.123/195.267 = 1.716 gives ~$107k/QALY (an earlier revision assumed 2008 dollars, ~$97k). The {30k, 220k} prior brackets that with room for cheaper high-need PSH cases (frequent cost offsets) and costlier general populations. [NASEM (2018)](https://nap.nationalacademies.org/read/25133/chapter/6) is cited for the mixed-evidence assessment only."
web/allocation_v10.json:4: "description": "The allocation as published with the July 13 geographic-routing correction: every 'global'-listed organization treated as fully non-US. Preserved for comparison; superseded by v1.1.",
