+# Red-team referee report — round 3
+
+| Round-2 item | Status | Verification against fresh text |
+|---:|---|---|
+| 1 | RESOLVED FOR WORKING PAPER | The standing decision to retain the headline estimate is now supported by explicit proxy/mixture caveats, an upward-bias limitation, and a no-geographic-repricing comparison of roughly 70,000 versus 202,000 QALYs. This is adequate scenario disclosure at SSRN stage. |
+| 2 | RESOLVED | The limitations now expressly say the estimate is not a floor on total wellbeing, identifies omitted harms, and explains that the near-RCT-only case is only the closest available zero scenario. |
+| 3 | RESOLVED FOR WORKING PAPER | The 19% audited-overlay estimate remains a heuristic without sampling bounds, but the paper now distinguishes the Dirichlet judgment prior from pipeline uncertainty and explicitly lists geography-audit uncertainty as unpropagated. This is a documented limitation. |
+| 4 | RESOLVED FOR WORKING PAPER | The reconciliation arithmetic is now internally correct: 33 were confirmed within tolerance, 17 disputed, four adjudicated, and all other final fractions average the coders. Confidence grades and source records are disclosed; further external validation can reasonably be deferred. |
+| 5 | RESOLVED FOR WORKING PAPER | The 95%/93% figures remain clearly labeled later-period, organization-wide proxies, and the scalar/regional-denominator mismatch remains disclosed as a limitation. The standing deferral is reasonable. |
+| 6 | RESOLVED | The frontier now shares only the realization draw and receives its stated RCT-grade credibility. The unsupported universal diminishing-returns claim is replaced by the narrower claim that the multiple remains large only at scales addressed by the cited benchmarks. |
+| 8 | RESOLVED | Priority is now Scott-specific (“first outside ... estimate of Scott's giving”), while the broader comparison is framed as the author's search result rather than an established universal. This is adequate for a working paper. |
+| 11 | RESOLVED FOR WORKING PAPER | Section 6 now accurately limits interpolation to the body and discloses that abstract figures are typed copies. A CI render guard remains deferred rather than falsely claimed. |
+| 13 | RESOLVED FOR WORKING PAPER | The unsupported “eleven rounds” count is gone, the latest transition has reproducible tags, and the table defines revisions and records the detector. Direct evidence links for every earlier row would improve the audit trail, but their absence is not material enough to block this working paper. |
+| 14 | RESOLVED FOR WORKING PAPER | Section 2.1 now specifies disclosure-year booking and the May 2026 CPI-U anchor; the nominal-share application and its very small effect remain disclosed in limitations. |
+| 15 | RESOLVED FOR WORKING PAPER | The elasticity is now called a within-sample regularity rather than a validated prediction rule, the full matched/unmatched flow is reported, and “representative” is explicitly conditional on the imputation model. |
+| New finding 1 | PARTIALLY RESOLVED | Section 2.3 correctly replaces “high-income regions” with “Europe & Central Asia plus Canada” and says the true high-income share is unidentified. Section 7, however, still calls those same dollars “high-income-region dollars,” contradicting that correction. Replace that phrase with “Europe & Central Asia plus Canada dollars” (or “possibly high-income dollars”) and keep the unidentified-share qualification. |
+| New finding 2 | RESOLVED | The foundation/public-filings extension is deleted. Transferability is now conditioned on disclosures carrying comparable gift-level allocation and geography fields. |
+
+## New findings
+
+None. A brief regression glance found no additional problem introduced by the newest edits. The one remaining factual wording mismatch is the unresolved tail of round 2's regional-classification finding above.
+
+RECOMMENDATION: Minor revisions

